    <title>Combined summary - Significant losses by double-spending unconfirmed transactions</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T02:48:17.281430+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-July/009423.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin-dev mailing list has been discussing various topics related to the Bitcoin network. One topic of discussion is Blockcypher's "confidence factor" model, which Peter Todd argues is a Sybil attack on the network. There is disagreement over whether Todd has evidence to back up this claim. The discussion then shifts to the concept of running many nodes on the network and whether it actually makes the network stronger in terms of reducing trust between participants.Another thread on the mailing list revolves around double-spending attacks against zeroconf accepting merchants. Users share their experiences with successful attacks and warn others to stop relying on zeroconf for transactions. Simon reports that Shapeshift.io lost around 3 BTC due to these types of attacks and is no longer accepting zeroconf. In another email exchange, Peter Todd discusses Sybil attacks in peer-to-peer networks with Matthieu from an unnamed company. They also discuss resource use and changing default configurations to offer more connections. Todd warns about achieving this through incoming connections as it places a significant part of the relay network under central control.The bitcoin-dev community discusses various issues related to the Bitcoin network and its vulnerabilities. A user named Arne asks for clarification on pre- and post-Hearn-relay drop rules and whether they have anything to do with the minrelaytxfee setting proposed in the 0.11.0 release notes. Another user, simongreen, shares their experience performing double-spend attacks against zeroconf accepting merchants and warns others to stop relying on zeroconf transactions. The discussion also includes warnings about Sybil attacks, the use of multiple nodes, and accusations of developer attacks lacking proper incentives. The writers suggest implementing a systematic risk analysis to reduce the probability of such an attack.There are also discussions about Chainalysis's services and Satoshi Dice, which are seen as not constituting attacks but rather services within the rules set forth in the software. The legitimacy of Peter Todd's double-spending demonstration is questioned, but later confirmed by Shapeshift.io who fell victim to the same attack. The bitcoin-dev community also discusses the potential of on-chain microtransaction systems and the need for the Bitcoin community to re-examine dust as an opportunity for microgiving.The context also warns against the vulnerabilities of zeroconf transactions, which are often used by merchants to process payments instantly without waiting for confirmations. The author suggests waiting for confirmations instead of relying on zeroconf transactions. Blockcypher's "confidence factor" model is criticized for being a sybil attacking network monitoring tool that uses up connection slots for the entire network. However, Blockcypher defends itself, stating that it only monitors such attacks and does not cause them. The context also includes discussions about resource use and changing default configurations to offer more connections, as well as the need for developers to perform systematic risk analysis to reduce the probability of developer attacks.In various discussions on the Bitcoin-Dev mailing list, several individuals shared their concerns and opinions on different topics related to Bitcoin. One user warned against the vulnerabilities of zeroconf transactions and described a strategy for double-spending attacks that has worked multiple times. This led to discussions on the reliability of zeroconf transactions and the importance of waiting for confirmations. Another user raised concerns about the business model of Blockcypher, accusing the company of performing a Sybil attack on the network. However, this accusation was refuted by the company's CEO, who stated that they were good actors in the space and constrained by limited resources. Additionally, there were discussions on the issue of developers making hyperbolic statements without proper analysis and characterizing user activities as spam and Sybil attacks.Finally, there were debates on whether running many nodes or connecting to a large percentage of nodes on the network can be considered a Sybil attack and how it can make the Bitcoin network less reliable. In conclusion, there is a need for systematic risk analysis to avoid making baseless statements and ensure the reliability and scalability of the Bitcoin network. The discussions cover various topics such as double-spending attacks, Sybil attacks, and the use of on-chain microtransaction systems. It is advised to be cautious when relying on unconfirmed transactions and to pay a good fee for highly relayable/minable transactions.</summary>
